idCitation.resTitle: Bull trout natal habitat patches under current and future climate scenarios for portions of Idaho, western Montana, eastern Oregon, and northern Nevada
idCitation.otherCitDet: Isaak, D., M. Young, D. Horan, D. Nagel, M. Schwartz, and K. McKelvey. 2022. Do metapopulations and management matter for relict headwater bull trout populations in a warming climate? Ecological Applications. DOI: 10.1002/eap.2594

dataIdInfo.idPurp: These streamline data consist of spatially contiguous stream reaches > 3 km in length representing suitable habitat patches for juvenile bull trout, chosen intentionally based on fish sample data and expert opinion. The reaches comprising these patches meet three criteria: 1) mean August stream temperatures < 11 °C; 2) summer discharge > 0.0057 m3/s, and 3) reach slopes < 15%. The streamlines were derived from 1:100,000 scale NHDPlus Version 2 digital data. These habitat patches were generated to test and validate bull trout habit occupancy models in the fish’s native range in portions of Idaho, western Montana, eastern Oregon, and northern Nevada. Each patch is attributed with various habitat characteristics identified as potentially important for predicting patch suitability for bull trout occupancy.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
Bull trout habitat patches for the fish’s natal life stage were generated for portions of Idaho, western Montana, eastern Oregon, and northern Nevada. Streamlines for the patches were derived from 1:100,000 scale NHDPlus Version 2 digital data (McKay et al., 2012). A custom geoprocessing script was used to generate the habitat patches based on the following criteria: 1) mean August stream temperatures < 11 °C (Isaak et al., 2017) that are suitable for juvenile bull trout; 2) summer discharge rates > 0.0057 m3/s (Wenger et al., 2012) to represent habitats large enough to be occupied by fish; and 3) reach slopes < 15% (McKay et al., 2012) to ensure accessibility for juvenile bull trout. Mean August stream temperature and summer discharge were downloaded from the NorWeST Regional Database and Modeled Stream Temperatures website: https://www.fs.fed.us/rm/boise/AWAE/projects/NorWeST.htmland the Western U.S. Stream Flow Metrics website: https://www.fs.fed.us/rm/boise/AWAE/projects/modeled_stream_flow_metrics.shtml. Reach slope was derived from the NHDPlus Version 2 dataset. Patches were further qualified using fish sample data and expert opinion.

Numerous descriptive attributes were associated with each patch to develop the occupancy model. These included: Elevation, patch length, patch volume, stream temperature, valley bottom confinement, reach slope, winter high flow frequency, average summer discharge, baseflow index, road density, riparian canopy cover, wildfire prevalence, network connectivity, brook trout prevalence, and adfluvial bull trout presence. Bull trout occupancy within each patch is also coded in the dataset. Each of these attributes and their various metrics are described in the attributes section of this metadata document along with detailed descriptions in the accompanying manuscript. See Appendix S3, Table S1.

Isaak, D., M. Young, D. Horan, D. Nagel, M. Schwartz, and K. McKelvey. 2022. Do metapopulations and management matter for relict headwater bull trout populations in a warming climate? Ecological Applications. DOI: 10.1002/eap.2594

dataLineage.statement:
Please note that each patch is made up of multiple COMIDs and often multiple GNIS stream names. Patches are dissolved into a single feature so all the stream-specific NHD information is removed. If users would like to find a specific stream, the HUC8 information can be used in conjunction with a spatial join or an underlying basemap.
For more information about lineage and procedures see the publication. Isaak, D., M. Young, D. Horan, D. Nagel, M. Schwartz, and K. McKelvey. 2022. Do metapopulations and management matter for relict headwater bull trout populations in a warming climate? Ecological Applications. DOI: 10.1002/eap.2594
